{"cursor":"12271","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Superherobox|  image= |caption=The\nMonitor. Art by George PÃ©rez |comic_color=background:#8080ff\n|character_name=The Monitor |real_name=Monitor |publisher=DC Comics |debut=(in\nshadows) [[Teen Titans#The New Teen Titans/The New Titans era (1980-1996)|The\nNew Teen Titans]] Vol. 2 #21 (July 1982) (fully seen) G.I. Combat #274\n(February 1985) |creators=Marv Wolfman George PÃ©rez\n|alliance_color=background:#ffc0c0 |alliances= |powers=Vast cosmic powers.\n|}}\n\nThe 'Monitor' is a fictional character created by writer Marv Wolfman In\nBatman and the Outsiders #14 (Oct. 1984), he is listed as having been \"created\nby 'Marv Wolfman', age 38, of Flushing, New York.\" (p. 12) and artist\nGeorge PÃ©rez as one of the main characters of DC Comics' [[Crisis on Infinite\nEarths]] limited series.\n\nThe character began appearing, along with his assistant Lyla, in numerous DC\nComics titles beginning in 1982, three years before the Crisis began in July\n1985; these appearances made it seem that he was some sort of weapons dealer for\nsupervillains. This was all part of the setup Wolfman and the staff of DC Comics\nplanned for the Crisis, showing the Monitor currying favor with villains such as\nMaxie Zeus, prior to calling on the heroes. Batman and the Outsiders #14\n(Oct. 1984) The Monitor was depicted in the shadows for all of his\nappearances in DC's mainstream superhero titles, and his face was first revealed\nin one of their few remaining non-superhero titles, the war comic [[G.I.\nCombat]] issue #274.\n","linknr":181,"url":"Monitor_(comics)","recorded":1363424354,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Monitor_(comics)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Monitor_(comics)&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentCh